article.description:
Allison Hightower scored 21 points and LaSondra Barrett had 12 as LSU upset Florida (No. 11 ESPN/USA Today, No. 9 AP)
 66-47 on Sunday.
article.headline: Hightower, Barrett lead way as Florida suffers second straight loss
article.linkText: LSU hands No. 11 Florida second straight loss
article.story:
BATON ROUGE, La. -- LSU had just the plan to take down Florida (No. 11 ESPN/USA Today, No. 9 AP).

The Tigers built a 16-2 lead in the game's first 10½ minutes and went on to beat Florida 66-47 Sunday.

"LSU hit us in the mouth and we spent the rest of the ballgame trying to get up off the floor," Florida coach Amanda Butler said.

Allison Hightower scored 21 points for LSU and LaSondra Barrett had 12 points and seven rebounds.

The Tigers (13-9, 6-4 SEC) got their first win in six tries against a ranked opponent. The Gators (22-4, 8-3) lost their second straight conference road game after an emotional 66-57 win at home last Sunday against Tennessee.

Florida lost Thursday at No. 24 Vanderbilt, 84-68.

"We've been anxious for one of these wins for a long time. Now we want to play off this momentum and carry it over to the rest of the season," LSU forward Kristen Morris said.

In a matchup of the SEC's best scoring defense and the SEC's second-ranked scoring offense, LSU's defense clearly had the upper hand.

LSU held Florida to season lows in points, field goal percentage (32.1 percent) and 3-point shooting (1 of 12).

The Tigers paid particular attention to Florida point guard Sha Brooks, who averaged 20 points in the Gators' 10 previous SEC contests.

Brooks scored 12 points but was 4-of-12 from the field and missed all five 3-pointers.

"I couldn't get the ball to our shooters when they were open," said Brooks, who committed seven turnovers and had just one assist. "I got frustrated out there."

"That's all I've been hearing all week, 'Brooks, Brooks, Brooks,'" LSU's Latear Eason said. "I wanted to come in today and stop her."

LSU coach Van Chancellor said his team, which features seven newcomers after reaching its fifth straight Women's Final Four a year ago, was searching for a signature win all season long.

"We had one today," Chancellor said. "This was a great win for us. We beat a really good team by 19 points."
